title: How have conception rates changed?
analysis_commentary: The rate of conception in under 18s has been decreasing over time from 46.6 per 1,000 population in 1998 to 30.7 per 1,000 population in 2011 – this is a decrease of 34.1%. In 1999, the Teenage Pregnancy Strategy was launched, which included a target to halve the under-18 conception rate between 1998 and 2010. Although progress in reducing the under-18 conception rate was made, we can see that the target of 23.3 per 1,000 population was missed by over 10 conceptions per 1,000 population. Despite the end of this strategy in 2010, the conception rate continued to fall in 2011.
data_source: Office of National Statistics, Conception Statistics
